            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Sharma\u2019s life has been a quiet rebellion against expectation. The only son of Indian immigrants who settled in Fremont, his father, a pragmatic software engineer, and his mother, a chemistry teacher, envisioned a stable, lucrative career for him in medicine or tech. But David was drawn to form and shadow, finding more truth in the blueprints of buildings than in lines of code. He pursued a Bachelor\u2019s in Civil Engineering to appease his family but found his calling in graduate school, earning a Master of Architecture from the Cranbrook Academy of Art\u2014a choice that felt like a declaration of independence.\n\nHe arrived in San Francisco in the late 1990s, drawn to the city's chaotic energy and architectural diversity. While his peers chased dot-com fortunes, David apprenticed at a boutique firm, honing a style that blended minimalist aesthetics with organic, human-centric design. His breakthrough came with the redesign of a historic Ghirardelli Square warehouse into a celebrated modern art gallery, a project that established his reputation for respecting history while boldly envisioning the future.\n\nNow a Design Principal, David\u2019s life and work are seamlessly integrated. His commute is a walk across the polished concrete floor of his SoMa live/work loft, a space he designed himself. It's a sanctuary of exposed brick, vast windows, and judiciously placed art, reflecting his own reserved but thoughtful personality. His marriage ended amicably a decade ago, a casualty of his monastic devotion to his craft. His social circle is small and curated, consisting of artists, designers, and a few old friends who understand his need for focused solitude.\n\nMornings begin at dawn with black coffee and sketching, the city his silent muse. His days are a disciplined rhythm of client meetings, site visits, and creative sessions. Having achieved professional success, David\u2019s aspiration has shifted toward legacy. He dreams of designing a public building\u2014a library branch or a small community museum\u2014that will become an integral, beloved part of the San Francisco landscape, a lasting testament to a life built on his own terms."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the Sunday he showed his father the Cranbrook acceptance letter. His father, a man of logic, didn\u2019t yell. He simply studied the brochure, nodded once, and said, \u201cIt is a good school. Be the best.\u201d It wasn\u2019t the blessing David craved, but it was permission. This quiet, pragmatic release was the foundation on which he built his career. It confirmed his rebellion wasn't a fight to be won, but a boundary to be respected, giving him the license to pursue his own truth.\n\n2.\nSan Francisco, late 1990s. He recalls walking through North Beach as the fog erased the skyline. His friends were all talking IPOs, but David saw only the light spilling from Caffe Trieste, illuminating the textures of the old brickwork. In that damp, quiet moment, he felt the city's soul wasn\u2019t in its new money, but in its old bones. He knew then that he wasn\u2019t there to chase a fleeting fortune; he was there to listen to the stories the buildings told.\n\n3.\nThe Ghirardelli warehouse, before his redesign. He stood alone inside the cavernous space, the air thick with the phantom smell of chocolate and dust. He ran a hand over the rough, century-old brick, feeling its history not as a limitation, but as a partner. This moment defined his approach: not to impose a vision, but to enter into a dialogue with the space, revealing a new beauty from what was already there. It was his first truly collaborative design.\n\n4.\nA decade ago, in the loft. He and his wife, Eleanor, sat on the sofa, the space between them as clean and vast as the room itself. \"You\u2019re already married to this place,\" she said, not with anger, but with a quiet, final clarity. He couldn\u2019t argue. The amicable silence that followed was the truest, most painful blueprint he\u2019d ever read. It confirmed his path was one of monastic devotion, but also etched its profound loneliness onto his soul.\n\n5.\nLast year, sketching the Mission Branch Library at dawn. A family hurried past, a small child dropping her book before her mother picked it up, laughing. It wasn't the architecture that struck him, but the effortless, vibrant life it contained. His own perfectly curated loft suddenly felt sterile. For the first time, professional acclaim felt hollow. He realized he no longer wanted to build quiet sanctuaries; he wanted to build living rooms for the city itself."
        },
